        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The proposed targets, NGC1313 X-2 and NGC 5408 X-1,  are at distances of 3.7 and 4.8 Mpc,
thus 1" corresponds to 18 pc and 24 pc, respectively.
If we observe these sources with the extended configuration, the angular resolution of 0.19 \arcsec, 
which enable us to resolve spatial structures at ~3.5 pc.
Since typical size of a GMC in the Galaxy is ~50 pc (Blitz 1993; Fukui and Kawamura 2010),
our proposed angular resolution is sufficient to spatially resolve the structure to see if 
detected emission comes from the dense gas in GMC associated with the ULXs.


Dense gas in GMCs is distributed smaller than ~50 pc corresponding to 2"~2.5" for the observing sources. 
So we require only the 12-m array are necessary to carry out our observations.


We are mainly going to use CN (2-1) lines in the following reason: First CN has a higher critical 
density than CO so that our observations do not suffer from contamination of extended emission. 
Second, previous study demonstrated that CN is a known good tracer of the XDR (Meijerink, Spaans, Israel 2007), 
expected around the ULXs.  
We use ``RADEX'' (Van der Tak et al. 2007) to calculate non-LTE molecular radiative 
transfer in an isothermal homogeneous medium. 
According to Meijerink, Spaans, Israel (2007), the
CN column-density becomes  about 40 times that of HCN
in the XDR  when the molecular-hydrogen density  is 10^6 cm^-3.
Conservatively, we assume N(CN)/N(HCN)= 10, and calculate the expected line flux of 
CN(2-1). We assume the HCN column density is 
10^{13} cm^{-2},  CN column density 10^{14} cm^{-2},
kinetic temperature 　30 K, and the line-width 2 km s^{-1}. 
Taking the normal HCN fractional abundance, this corresponds to H_2 of 10^{22} cm^{-2}.
Consequently, using RADEX, we obtain the radiation temperature of the CN (2-1) spectral line
(226.8765 GHz) as 5.1 K.

Using the Observing Tool, putting the sensitivity 5 K with the Representative Window Resolution mode,
we require 5.63 hours in total for both sources.

In addition to the CN (2-1) line, we observe CO(2-1) and CS(5-4) lines in a similar setup which also are expected to trace the molecular material.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
