    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Ultra-luminous X-ray Sources (ULX) are bright compact X-ray sources often found in nearby spiral galaxies.  Because  their luminosities (~10^40-10^42 erg/s) largely exceed Eddington limits  of the Galactic compact objects (&lt;10^39 erg/s), they are considered either extremely massive stellar black holes (&lt; 30 Msolar) shining at super-Eddington luminosities, or a new type of "intermediate mass black holes (IMBHs)" (&gt;100M solar) shining at sub-Eddington luminosities.  Here, we propose a novel method to constrain the black hole mass in ULXs by measuring the position-velocity (PV) map of the Giant  Molecular Clouds (GMCs) surrounding the ULXs.  As a pilot study, we propose to observe two nearby ULXs, NGC 1313 X-2 and NGC 5408 X-1, which are known to be associated with optical or radio nebulae.  We  mainly use the  CS (2-1) line, which is expected from  the X-ray Dominant region in the center of the ULXs.  With the nominal performance of Cycle 2 (angular resolution of ~0."19 and velocity resolution of ~0.04 km/s),  we will be able to measure the Kepler velocities down to a radius of ~3.5 pc, and draw the PV-diagram to tell if there is an IMBH at the center of the ULX or not.
</prp:abstract>
